<button class="accordion">What is an agency worker?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Generally, an agency worker is an individual supplied by employment businesses to a client to work under the client's direction and supervision.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Who can benefit from mandatory training for agency workers?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Mandatory training for agency workers may be beneficial for NHS doctors and medical locums, private-sector doctors, agency nurses, allied health professions (AHPs) and health and social care workers.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the most common subjects for mandatory training for agency workers?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The most common mandatory training subjects for agency workers include:</p>
<p></p><li>Health and safety</li>
<p></p><li>Fire safety</li>
<p></p><li>Equality, diversity and Human Rights</li>
<p></p><li>Infection, prevention and control</li>
<p></p><li>Manual handling</li>
<p></p><li>Food Hygiene/Food Safety Awareness</li>
<p></p><li>Safeguarding Adults</li>
<p></p><li>Safeguarding Children.</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is mandatory training?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Mandatory training is determined primarily by an organisation for the safe and efficient running to reduce organisational risks and comply with policies, government guidelines.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Who is this mandatory training for agency workers course for?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Locum doctors should complete this mandatory online training for agency workers package, as well as medical locums and other healthcare locum workers in NHS Trusts, private hospitals and other clinical settings including:</p>
<p></p><li>NHS consultants</li>
<p></p><li>Consultants working in the private sector</li>
<p></p><li>General practitioners</li>
<p></p><li>Locum GPs</li>
<p></p><li>Specialist registrars</li>
<p></p><li>Senior house officers</li>
<p></p><li>Private independent doctors</li>
<p></p><li>Locum nurses</li>
<p></p><li>Agency nurses</li>
<p></p><li>Allied health professionals 9AHPs</li>
<p></p><li>NHS healthcare professionals</li>
<p></p><li>Private healthcare professional</li>
<p></p><li>Healthcare assistants</li>
<p></p><li>Clinical support workers.</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the difference between statutory and mandatory training?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>On the one hand, statutory training is necessary to ensure that the organisation is meeting any legislative duties. On the other hand, mandatory training is an organisational requirement to limit risk and maintain a safe working practice.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Are employers required to provide mandatory training for agency workers?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Employers must provide training to any employee required by OSHA regulations. </p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is mandatory training for agency workers compensable?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>As a result, the time spent in mandatory training is generally compensable. According to the information provided, the training transpires during regular work hours.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is mandatory training for agency workers at work paid?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Yes. If you are required to attend a training program for work, you must be paid for that time. Thus, if your employer requires all new employees to participate in an orientation training or requires current employees to attend sexual harassment training, that time must be paid.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Does an employer have to pay you for mandatory training for agency workers?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>As mandatory training counts as work, they're covered by federal wage and hour laws. You have to be paid at least minimum wage while you participate in mandatory training.</p>
<p>However, the law allows your employer to pay you less than your average salaries for the training time.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Can I get fired for not going to mandatory training for agency workers?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Yes, you can be fired for not attending a mandatory meeting with one very narrow exception that likely will not apply to you. The basic rule is that you are an at will.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the difference between an agency worker and a carer?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A carer is anyone who, in an unpaid capacity, supports a loved one suffering from an illness, physical disability, mental health condition or addiction. Meanwhile, an agency worker is a paid professional who works in a variety of settings, from home agencies and residential agency facilities.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Who is responsible for agency workers?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Agency workers might be employees of the agency or employees of the business. Occasionally, agency workers are self-employed/freelance.</p>
<p>If you are the employer, you cannot transfer your health and safety responsibilities to another person or business.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What skills do you need to be an agency worker?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>To be an effective agency worker, you must have:</p>
<p></p><li>An interest in people and a commitment to helping others</li>
<p></p><li>The ability to communicate clearly and sensitively with vulnerable people and their families</li>
<p></p><li>Knowledge of the emotional and practical difficulties a client may face</li>
<p></p><li>Good listening skills</li>
<p></p><li>An empathetic approach to clients.</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the three primary responsibilities of an agency worker?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The three main duties of an agency worker are as follows:</p>
<p></p><li>Take all reasonable precautions to protect the health and safety of workers.</li>
<p></p><li>Ensure that equipment, materials and protective equipment are maintained in good condition.</li>
<p></p><li>Provide information, instruction and supervision to protect worker health and safety.</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do agency workers get sick pay?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>As an agency worker, you will be entitled to Statutory Sick Pay (SSP) if: your average weekly earnings exceed 118 a week (if your pay varies, your entitlement depends on your average salary over the previous eight weeks).</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do agency workers have rights?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Some agency workers are classified as employees. Employees are employed under a contract of service or contract of employment. They have all the rights workers have plus others, such as being paid if work is unavailable.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do agency workers get paid holidays?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Yes. You should receive at least 5.6 weeks' paid holiday a year. In particular, since 1 October 2011, temporary agency workers have had the right to the same holiday entitlement (pro-rata to their hours) as a comparable direct-hire employed by the hirer to do the same job.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the importance of mandatory training for agency workers?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Mandatory training for agency workers is necessary to support a safe and efficient practice, as well as to reduce organisational risks, comply with regulatory requirements and local policies.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How do employment agencies work?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>At a staffing agency, companies pay the agency to find employees for them. Job seekers can apply to specific jobs through the staffing agency or contact the staffing agency looking for a job. The agency interviews the job seekers and places them in appropriate positions.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do agency workers get a pension?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>An agency must auto-enrol all its agency workers into a pension scheme within three months of the start of the contract. If an agency worker does not want to be enrolled in the agency's pension scheme, they must contact the agency and the pension provider and opt-out of the system.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Are agency workers self-employed?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>You are an agency worker if you have a contract with an agency, who can then work temporarily for an employer. You might also be called a temp.</p>
<p>When you're working on a job, the employer controls your work. Hence, you are not self-employed.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How much do staffing agencies take from your pay?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Staffing/recruiting/employment agencies are the same thing. Their methods, services and agreements may differ, but the name doesn't change anything. Standard bill rate is a 40-50% markup on the hourly rate the temp employee gets. The standard direct placement fee is 25-30% of the total first-year compensation.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the benefits of multiagency working?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Some studies focused on the perceived benefits of multiagency working. The most improved and commonly identified useful service is joint problem-solving. However, the ability to take a holistic approach and increased understanding and trust between agencies were also cited.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why is multi-agency working important?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Multi-agency working is about providing a seamless response to individuals with multiple and complex needs. It is vital if individuals are to be offered the range of support they require promptly. </p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Are employment agencies for agency workers regulated?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>All agencies, whether or not they are REC members, must follow two pieces of legislation, the Employment Agencies Act 1973 (EAA) and the Conduct of Employment Agencies and Employment Business Regulations 2003 (Conduct Regulations).</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Can I work for two agencies at the same time?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>An employee can work two different types of jobs within the same company. The employer wants to track how much time the employee spends on each post, so the employer has him use two different time clocks. An employee finds work through two various staffing agencies for the same employer.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is this mandatory training for agency workers accredited?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>On successful completion of each of the mandatory online training for agency nurses courses, you will be able to download, save, and print a quality assured continuing professional development (CPD) certificate. Our CPD certificates are recognised internationally and can be used to provide evidence for compliance and audit.</p>
<p><a href="https://cpduk.co.uk/directory/profile/the-mandatory-training-group"><font color="green"><u>The CPD Certification Service (CPDUK)</u></font></a>accredits all of our statutory and mandatory training courses as conforming to universally accepted Continuous Professional Development (CPD) guidelines.</p>
</div>

